{"questionId":"3244659","questionHtml":"<p>Petra examines two quantities, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>, and plots data points on a log-log graph.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/3abf159837e8e2778bf6612dbb1ee5f0c81b1a10.png\"></p>\n<p>She observes that on this graph the data points follow a perfect straight line. Given that the line passes through the points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1951</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>822</mn><mo>)</mo></math>, find the equation of the relationship connecting <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>. Your final answer should not include logarithms.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1 Analytical approach</strong></p>\n<p>recognizing that the linear equation must be expressed in log form &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo> </mo><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>c</mi></math> (or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>m</mi><mo> </mo><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>C</mi></math>)</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>use of slope formula (must involve logs) &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong> (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>822</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1951</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>log</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to substitute a value&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>log</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1951</mn><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>log</mi><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>(</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>69897</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>)</mo></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>.</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>m</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>attempt to set up two equations involving power functions&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1951</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi></msup></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>822</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>4</mn><mi>m</mi></msup></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>34</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>822</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1951</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>639</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>⇒</mo><mi>m</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>log</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>639</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>c</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1951</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>639</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p>(so the equation is) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>METHOD 2 Regression analysis</strong></p>\n<p>recognizing that a log-log graph results in a power function model&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp; (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mi>b</mi></msup></math></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>attempt to find a power regression model using the given two points&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>(so the equation is) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>A2</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[6 marks]</strong></em>&nbsp;</p>","meta":{"questionId":"3244659","referenceCode":"23M.1.AHL.TZ1.14","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Petra examines two quantities, x and y, and plots data points on a log-log graph. She observes that on this graph the data points follow a perfect straight line. Given that the lin","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"14","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 6]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 2—Functions","AHL 2.10—Scaling large numbers, log-log graphs"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}